[{"id":"VR914698","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\"><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows three diagrams that are labeled “Setup, Side View,” “Card With Vertical Slit, Front View,” and “Viewing Screen, Front View.” The Setup, Side View diagram shows a laser, a card, and a screen on a horizontal surface. The laser is on the left, a card with a vertical slit is in the middle, and a viewing screen is on the right. The horizontal distance between the card and the viewing screen is labeled uppercase D. The laser directs a laser beam horizontally to the right through the vertical slit of the card. The laser beam continues to move horizontally to the right and ends on the viewing screen. The Card With Vertical Slit, Front View diagram shows the card, represented by a gray square. The vertical slit is represented by a short, thin rectangle at the center of the square. The vertical slit has width w. A small white circle, representing the laser beam, is shown at the center of the square. The white circle has radius r and completely surrounds the vertical slit. The Viewing Screen, Front View diagram shows the pattern formed by the laser beam on the viewing screen. The background of the viewing screen is black. The pattern is comprised of seven shapes that are evenly spaced from each other. From left to right, the pattern is as following: square, square, square, rectangle, square, square, and square. The rectangle is labeled Central Bright Fringe. The horizontal distance from the midpoint of the space to the left of the Central Bright Fringe, to the midpoint of the space to the right of the Central Bright Fringe is labeled lowercase d.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR914698.g02.svg\"/></div></div></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">The figure shows a setup with a laser that shines light of wavelength <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"lambda\"><math alttext=\"lambda\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>λ</mi></math></span></span> onto a card with a narrow vertical slit of width <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"w\"><math alttext=\"w\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>w</mi></math></span></span>. The laser beam illuminates a circle of radius <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"r\"><math alttext=\"r\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>r</mi></math></span></span> on the card, where <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"r is greater than w\"><math alttext=\"r is greater than w\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>r</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mi>w</mi></math></span></span>. A viewing screen located a distance <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"uppercase D\"><math alttext=\"uppercase D\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>D</mi></math></span></span> from the card shows the resulting diffraction pattern. In the diffraction pattern, <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"d\"><math alttext=\"d\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>d</mi></math></span></span> is the center-to-center distance between the two dark fringes that are adjacent to the central bright fringe. Which of the following approximates the distance <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"d\"><math alttext=\"d\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>d</mi></math></span></span>? Assume that small-angle approximations are valid for the fringes shown in the diffraction pattern.</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR914698_rubric","choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"the fraction with numerator lambda times uppercase D, and denominator w, end fraction\"><math alttext=\"the fraction with numerator lambda times uppercase D, and denominator w, end fraction\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>λ</mi><mi>D</mi></mrow><mi>w</mi></mfrac></math></span></span></p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"the fraction with numerator 2 lambda times uppercase D, and denominator w, end fraction\"><math alttext=\"the fraction with numerator 2 lambda times uppercase D, and denominator w, end fraction\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>λ</mi><mi>D</mi></mrow><mi>w</mi></mfrac></math></span></span></p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"the fraction with numerator lambda times uppercase D, and denominator r, end fraction\"><math alttext=\"the fraction with numerator lambda times uppercase D, and denominator r, end fraction\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>λ</mi><mi>D</mi></mrow><mi>r</mi></mfrac></math></span></span></p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"the fraction with numerator lambda times uppercase D, and denominator 2 r, end fraction\"><math alttext=\"the fraction with numerator lambda times uppercase D, and denominator 2 r, end fraction\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>λ</mi><mi>D</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>r</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></span></span></p>"],"answer":1}]